<section xml:id="lesson5_2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
   <title>Mathematical Models</title>

   <p>
      What is a mathematical model?</p>

   <p> A <term>mathematical model</term> predicts the behavior of some predictable process, like
      dividing a pie between a group of people. In order to solve these problems mathematically, we
      need a few things:</p>
   <p>
      <ul>
         <li>Mathematical symbols to express the parts of the problem.</li>
         <li>Mathematical operations to follow to calculate the result.</li>
      </ul>
   </p>

   <p>If those don't exist, then people invent new symbols and define new operations that properly
      predict the observed behavior.
      The main point is that the mathematics is derived from observations of the real world, not the
      other way around. </p>

   <section xml:id="fractions_mathematical_model" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <title>Mathematical model for fractions</title>

      <p>I'll explain this using a familiar mathematical model: fractions! Consider the following
         problem:</p>

      <p>
         <ul>
            <li>You have a pie to share with three friends. </li>
            <li>You cut it into 4 equal pieces.</li>
            <li>Your friend exclaims, “Just because there are four of us, it doesn't mean we need to
               eat the whole pie! I only want half that much!!” </li>
            <li>How much of the pie will you give your friend? </li>
         </ul>
      </p>

      <p> You are probably so used to solving problems like this, that you don't think about all the
         steps that go into solving it with fractions!
         Let's explore those aspects.</p>

      <subsection>
         <title> Representing fractional state</title>

         <p> We say “one fourth,” which could translate to “if that were divided into 4 equal-sized
            parts, then I want one of them.” We also represent this mathematically with the number
            of parts you want (numerator) placed over the total number of parts (denominator) with a
            line in between. We can either display it with the numerator above the denominator with
            a horizontal line in between or a 1 to the left of the 4 with a diagonal line in
            between. However, you cannot display it <m>1 \text{\\} 4</m>. </p>

         <p>
            <md>\frac{1}{4} \text{ or } ¼</md>
         </p>

         <p>This allows us to more clearly state the problem:</p>

         <p>
            <ul>
               <li>You have a pie to share with three friends. </li>
               <li>You cut it into 4 equal pieces, each 1/4 of the pie.</li>
               <li>Your friend exclaims, “Just because there are four of us, it doesn't mean we need
                  to
                  eat the whole pie! I only want 1/2 a piece!!” </li>
               <li>How much of the pie will you give your friend? </li>
            </ul>
         </p>
      </subsection>

      <subsection>
         <title>Performing operations</title>

         <p>To multiply fractions, we perform this set of operations:</p>

         <p>
            <ul>
               <li>Multiply the numerators. </li>
               <li>Multiply the denominators.</li>
               <li>Simplify if necessary.</li>
            </ul>
         </p>

         <p>
            <md>
               \frac{1}{4} \times \frac{1}{2} = \frac{(1 \times 1)}{(4 \times 2)} = \frac{1}{8}
            </md>
         </p>

         <p>Now let's consider a slightly different question:</p>

         <p>
            <ul>
               <li>You brought two pies to a potluck, pecan pie and apple pie. </li>
               <li>Both pies have the same radius, but the pecan pie is much more intense than the
                  apple pie,
                  so you cut smaller pieces; You cut the pecan pie into 10 pieces and the apple pie
                  into 8 pieces. </li>
               <li>It is time to gather your leftovers. The pecan pie has 5 pieces left, and the
                  apple
                  pie has 3 pieces left. </li>
               <li>How much total pie is there left?</li>
            </ul>
         </p>

         <p> To solve this, you would perform the following steps:</p>
         <p>
            <ul>
               <li>Express the leftover pecan pie as a fraction: <m>\frac{5}{10}</m>
               </li>
               <li> Simplify the pecan pie fraction to be <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>
               </li>
               <li>Express the leftover apple pie as a fraction: <m>\frac{3}{8}</m></li>
               <li>Add the fractions </li>
            </ul>
         </p>

         <p>Easy-peasy lemon-squeezy, right? Addition is easier than multiplication, so adding these
            fractions should be a
            piece of cake (or pie), right? </p>

         <p>To add fractions, we perform this set of operations:</p>
         <p>
            <ul>
               <li>Find the least common denominator (<m>\text{LCD}</m>) </li>
               <li>Multiply the first numerator by <m>\frac{\text{LCD}}{\text{1st denominator}}</m></li>
               <li>Multiply the second numerator by <m>\frac{\text{LCD}}{\text{2nd denominator}}</m></li>
               <li>Add the numerators and retain the common denominator</li>
               <li>Simplify if necessary </li>
            </ul>
         </p>

         <p>
            <md>
               \frac{5}{10} + \frac{3}{8} =
               \frac{1}{2} + \frac{3}{8} =
               \frac{4}{8} + \frac{3}{8} =
               \frac{(4 + 3)}{8} =
               \frac{7}{8}
            </md>
         </p>

         <p> I know what you're thinking, "Now you just hold on a <!-- cotton-pickin' --> minute. That didn't seem easier
            at all!" I must agree with you there. How about we look at an alternate representation:
            Decimals.</p>

      </subsection>
   </section>

   <section xml:id="decimals_mathematical_model" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <title>Mathematical model for decimals</title>
      <p>Notice that if we had expressed these operations as decimals, then the operations would
         have been performed differently.
         Consider those two questions again.</p>

      <paragraphs>
         <title>Multiplication using decimals</title>
         <p>You cut your pie into 4 pieces, so each piece has size <m>0.25</m>. Your friend only wants
            half a piece, which is expressed as <m>0.5</m>. Thus to calculate how much of the pie you
            give your friend, you multiply the two:</p>

         <ol>
            <li>Multiply the two numbers, ignoring the decimal place</li>
            <li>Add the number of digits after the decimal in each number, and put the decimal
               point
               this many digits in from the right</li>
         </ol>

         <p>In our case, this means:</p>

         <ol>
            <li>
               <m>25 \times 5 = 125</m>
            </li>
            <li>The total number of decimal places is <m>2 + 1 = 3</m></li>
            <li>Thus, <m>0.25 \times 0.5 = 0.125</m></li>
         </ol>
      </paragraphs>

      <paragraphs>
         <title>Addition using decimals</title>
         <p> We have 5 of the 10 pieces of pecan pie left, which is expressed as <m>0.5</m>. We also
            have 3 of the 8 pieces of apple pie left, which is expressed as <m>0.375</m>. To calculate
            how much total pie we have left, we add the two: </p>

         <ol>
            <li>Align the two numbers by their decimal point, adding trailing zeroes after the
               decimal if needed</li>
            <li>Add the two as with regular numbers, and keep the decimal point where it is</li>
         </ol>

         <p>In our case, this means:</p>

         <ol>
            <li>
               <m>0.5 + 0.375 = 0.500 + 0.375</m>
            </li>
            <li>
               <m>0.500 + 0.375 = 0.875</m>
            </li>
         </ol>
      </paragraphs>

      <p> In this case, addition is easier than multiplication. In fact, multiplication has an
         addition step!</p>
   </section>

   <conclusion>
      <p>The important takeaway here is the following:</p>

      <p> The mathematical representation you use had advantages and
         disadvantages in terms of readiability vs computation difficulty.
         Fractions are very easy to interpret visually, but they are harder to perform addition.
         Decimals are sometimes harder to interpret, but addition and
         multiplication are easier than with fractions.</p>

      <p> We are going to see the same tradeoffs in representing quantum state and performing
         quantum operations. We are going to learn two
         ways to express state: one that clearly shows the probabilities, and another that
         corresponds with how to perform operations.</p>
   </conclusion>

</section>
